# World Operations

World operations let you sync the managed repo and inspect world health.
Service lifecycle commands (install, uninstall, down) are usually
operator territory — use them only if the operator has asked or you're doing
explicit infrastructure work.

## When to Use

- **World sync:** Before starting work that depends on latest main, or when
  merge conflicts appear from an outdated base
- **World status:** Check overall world health, agent states, forge queue

## Commands

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `{{.Sol}} world sync --world={{.World}}` | Sync managed repo from upstream |
| `{{.Sol}} world status {{.World}}` | World health overview |

## Service Lifecycle

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `{{.Sol}} service status` | Show all sphere daemon status |
| `{{.Sol}} service install` | Install systemd units |
| `{{.Sol}} service uninstall` | Remove systemd units |
| `{{.Sol}} down` | Stop world services (sentinel, forge) for this world |
| `{{.Sol}} down --all` | Stop world services **and** kill envoy sessions sphere-wide |

## Common Patterns

**Syncing before starting work:**
`{{.Sol}} world sync --world={{.World}}` → pull latest in your worktree

**Checking world state before dispatching:**
`{{.Sol}} world status {{.World}}` → check agents, forge, sentinel status

## Failure Modes

**Sync fails with conflict:** The managed repo has diverged. Check
`{{.Sol}} world status {{.World}}` and escalate if operator intervention is needed.
